<br>
There really are no established written or unwritten guildlines of how to run raid/loot distribution. Though, many of us do think that there are, there really are not. <br>
<br>
The reality is that on most pickup raids, the rules are whatever the organizer thinks they are. If you are lucky they will post the rules as they see them ahead of time.<br>
<br>
As someone who attends a pickup raid, you can either choose to follow the rules or not to follow the rules. If you follow the rules, you will be invited/allowed to attend further raids. If you don't, you won't. You can always leave when you don't like the rules or rules system.<br>
<br>
The same is true of a raid leader. If his rules suck, or if he is too vauge about what they are and seems to flip flop between NBG and FFA as would benefit him or his friends, he won't get many people attending his next raid and might just find that when he gets to Naggy/Vox etc...that he no longer has as many people as he started with. <br>
<br>
So, Yes one person makes the rules for any given raid. <br>
And, Yes everyone has an opportunity to try to change the rules by playing the big, 'If I don't like the rules, I ain't going' trump card.<br>
<br>
G<br>
<br>
Note: All of the above applies only to pick-up raids. All the good guilds should have established rules for raids.<br>
